=80=99s also where many of the world=E2=80=99s most powerful people go when=
 they=E2=80=99re feeling curious, feisty, inspired, or just bored. I don=E2=
=80=99t know anyone who checks LinkedIn as compulsively as Twitter.=C2=A0
Engaging. And when they check, they engage. This image that Ben Thompson in=
cluded in his recent Back to the Future of Twitter [ https://email.mg2.subs=
tack.com/c/eJxFkEuOhSAQRVfzmGn4-hkw6ElvwyCUSlrBQNEv7r7xOeiEUAmXqlv3WIOwxnTp=
M2Yk9zXhdYIO8M47IEIiJUOavNOs44NQciROS8cGNRCfpyUBHMbvGlMBcpZ599agj-HTQSlXZNO=
MjaYXrFcLm51ZGAhpQFiqmKWiB_P4muI8BAsafiFdMQDZ9YZ45pf4evHvejKmuq7dqtzaeNQXTj=
mvZTb2p8HY4AbNUrAkaOLS4NvfAapOvL5_UkVHxpVgQytaxWk3guwZ50xxPr8kPVbe5jJnrONuA=
5J0iDjH5MNa5Z_NHLB_hBp0qvUoweM1QTDzDu5hgA_KD5VphQD3zm4yWAEqXpEMdJQdfzJXSEqy=
ulgnSXV2sXaFf9M_uyKKWw ] captures the difference between how users interact=
 with Twitter and Instagram well.=C2=A0
Valuable. There=E2=80=99s a question that goes around Twitter every so ofte=
n that goes something like =E2=80=9CHow much would someone have to pay you =
to not use Twitter?=E2=80=9D I asked it myself while I was writing this pie=
ce, and the answer is eye-popping but not surprising. Across over 1,100 res=
ponses to my very unscientific poll, 40% of respondents said they=E2=80=99d=
 need to be paid more than $10,000 per year to not use Twitter.=C2=A0
Again, not scientific, but I think it=E2=80=99s directionally accurate for =
a subset of Twitter=E2=80=99s most valuable users =E2=80=93 the =E2=80=9CCr=
eators=E2=80=9D who send 80% of all tweets=C2=A0 =E2=80=93 and specifically=
 the subset of that group whose business or income benefits from Twitter. F=
or that 40%, Twitter is leaving so much money on the table that you can=E2=
=80=99t even see its current ARPU on the graph unless I make it really tall=
=2E=C2=A0
I don=E2=80=99t think Twitter should start charging power users $10,000 per=
 year (Elon: please don=E2=80=99t start charging power users $10,000 per ye=
ar), but there=E2=80=99s somewhere between the $0 it currently charges and =
the $10,000+ people would be willing to pay that Twitter can charge its use=
rs for a better user experience and access to better products from Twitter =
(or built on Twitter).=C2=A0
Twitter doesn=E2=80=99t need to build the biggest network in the world to b=
e wildly successful. It just needs to make sure it serves its smaller segme=
nt of higher-value users better, and monetizes them much better, than it do=
es today.=C2=A0
That view informs what I think New Twitter should build.
To learn what I think Twitter should build and how a TweeterDAO might work=
